UninterpretedOption.docs:
A message representing a option the parser does not recognize. This only
 appears in options protos created by the compiler::Parser class.
 DescriptorPool resolves these when building Descriptor objects. Therefore,
 options protos in descriptor objects (e.g. returned by Descriptor::options(),
 or produced by Descriptor::CopyTo()) will never have UninterpretedOptions
 in them.

Comparator.docs:
The Comparator specifies the set of supported comparison operations. It also provides the
 mapping information about which comparators are supported for which values. Services that wish
 to implement entity filters must provide validation functionality to strictly enforce these
 mappings.

ListComparator.docs:
The ListComparator determines how to compose statement evaluations for members of a list. For
 example, if ANY_OF is specified, the ListOperation in which the ListComparator is embedded
 will return TRUE if any of the values in the list returns true for the ListOperation's child
 statement.

Statement.docs:
A Statement is the building block of the entity filter. The outermost statement is conceptually
 the root node of an "expression tree" which allows for the construction of complete boolean
 logic statements. Statements are formed by grouping sets of children statement(s) or predicate(s)
 according to the boolean operation which is to be applied.

 For example, the criteria "take an action if an entity is hostile and an air vehicle" can be
 represented as: Statement1: { AndOperation: { Predicate1, Predicate2 } }. Where Statement1
 is the root of the expression tree, with an AND operation that is applied to children
 predicates. The predicates themselves encode "entity is hostile" and "entity is air vehicle."

AndOperation.docs:
The AndOperation represents the boolean AND operation, which is to be applied to the list of
 children statement(s) or predicate(s).

OrOperation.docs:
The OrOperation represents the boolean OR operation, which is to be applied to the list of
 children statement(s) or predicate(s).

NotOperation.docs:
The NotOperation represents the boolean NOT operation, which can only be applied to a single
 child predicate or statement.

PredicateSet.docs:
The PredicateSet represents a list of predicates or "leaf nodes" in the expression tree, which
 can be directly evaluated to a boolean TRUE/FALSE result.

StatementSet.docs:
The StatementSet represents a list of statements or "tree nodes," each of which follow the same
 behavior as the Statement proto message.

Predicate.docs:
The Predicate fully encodes the information required to make an evaluation of an entity field
 against a given static value, resulting in a boolean TRUE/FALSE result. The structure of a
 predicate will always follow: "{entity-value} {comparator} {fixed-value}" where the entity value
 is determined by the field path.

 For example, a predicate would read as: "{entity.location.velocity_enu} {LESS_THAN} {500kph}"

Value.docs:
The Value represents the information against which an entity field is evaluated. It is one of
 a fixed set of types, each of which correspond to specific comparators. See "ComparatorType"
 for the full list of Value <-> Comparator mappings.

BooleanType.docs: The BooleanType represents a static boolean value.

NumericType.docs:
The NumericType represents static numeric values. It supports all numeric primitives supported
 by the proto3 language specification.

StringType.docs: The StringType represents static string values.

EnumType.docs:
The EnumType represents members of well-known anduril ontologies, such as "disposition." When
 such a value is specified, the evaluation library expects the integer representation of the enum
 value. For example, a disposition derived from ontology.v1 such as "DISPOSITION_HOSTILE" should be
 represented with the integer value 2.

ListType.docs: A List of Values for use with the IN comparator.

TimestampType.docs: The TimestampType represents a static timestamp value.

PositionType.docs: The PositionType represents any fixed LLA point in space.

BoundedShapeType.docs: The BoundedShapeType represents any static fully-enclosed shape.

HeadingType.docs:
The HeadingType represents the heading in degrees for an entity's
 attitudeEnu quaternion to be compared against. Defaults between a range of 0 to 360

RangeType.docs:
The RangeType represents a numeric range.
 Whether endpoints are included are based on the comparator used.
 Both endpoints must be of the same numeric type.

DynamicStatement.docs:
A DynamicStatement is the building block of a "runtime aware" entity filter - that is, any filter
 which needs to perform operations against a series of entities that will need to be evaluated against
 on demand. The DynamicStatement allows you to perform a set intersection operation across a static
 set of entities dictated by a filter, and a dynamic set of entities dictated by a selector statement.

 For example, the expression "find me all hostile entities that reside within any assumed
 friendly geoentity" would be represented as the following dynamic statement:

  DynamicStatement
    filter
      predicate
        field_path: mil_view.disposition
        comparator: EQUALITY
        value: 2 // Hostile
    selector
      andOperation
        predicate1
          field_path: mil_view.disposition
          comparator: EQUALITY
          value: 4 // Assumed Friendly
        predicate2
          field_path: ontology.template
          comparator: EQUALITY
          value: 4 // Template Geo
    comparator

IntersectionComparator.docs:
The IntersectionComparator determines what entities and what fields to respect within a set during
 a set intersection operation.

WithinComparison.docs:
The WithinComparison implicitly will understand how to determine which entitites reside
 within other geo-shaped entities. This comparison is being left empty, but as a proto, to
 support future expansions of the within comparison (eg; within range of a static distance).

values.docs: Task was cancelled by requester.
Task was rejected by assignee, see message for details.
Task Manager gave up waiting for a receipt/ack from assignee.
Task attempted to execute, but failed.

ErrorCode.docs: Error code associated with a Task error.

values.docs: Represents the most recent version of the Task known to Task Manager
Represents the most recent version of the Task acknowledged or updated by an Agent

TaskView.docs:
View of a Task through its lifecycle.
 For example, a definition v1 of a task may be running on an agent, indicated by TASK_VIEW_AGENT,
 while the definition v2 may not have been received yet, indicated by TASK_VIEW_MANAGER.

Task.docs: A Task is something an agent can be asked to do.

TaskStatus.docs:
TaskStatus is contains information regarding the status of a Task at any given time. Can include related information
  such as any progress towards Task completion, or any associated results if Task completed.

TaskError.docs: TaskError contains an error code and message typically associated to a Task.

Principal.docs: A Principal is an entity that has authority over this Task.

System.docs: System Principal representing some autonomous system.

User.docs: A User Principal representing a human.

Relations.docs: Relations describes the relationships of this Task, such as assignment, or if the Task has any parents.

TaskEvent.docs: Holds Tasks and its associated Events, e.g. CREATED.

DefinitionUpdate.docs: Message representing a Task create or update.

Owner.docs: Owner designates the entity responsible for writes of Task data.

Replication.docs: Any metadata associated with the replication of a Task.

Allocation.docs: Allocation contains a list of agents allocated to a Task.

TaskEntity.docs: Wrapper of an entity passed in Tasking, used to hold an additional information, and as a future extension point.

CreateTaskResponse.docs: Response to a Create Task request.

GetTaskResponse.docs: Response to a Get Task request.

QueryTasksRequest.TimeRange.docs: A time range query for Tasks.

QueryTasksRequest.docs: Request to query for Tasks. Returns the each latest Task by Status ID and Version ID by default with no filters.

QueryTasksResponse.docs: Response to a Query Task request.

UpdateStatusRequest.docs: Request to update a Task's status.

UpdateStatusResponse.docs: Response to an Update Status request.

ListenAsAgentRequest.docs: Request for streaming Tasks ready for agent execution.

ListenAsAgentResponse.docs: Response for streaming Tasks ready for agent execution.

SetPowerState.docs: Set the power state of a robot. It is up to the robot to interpret the power state and act accordingly.

DeleteTrack.docs:
Delete an entity from the internal tracker of a Platform.
 Does not silence or suppress the track from re-forming if the tracking conditions are satisfied.

SetHighPriorityTrack.docs:
Set this entity as a "High Priority Track".
 The tasked Platform is responsible for maintaining a list of current High-Priority tracks.

RemoveHighPriorityTrack.docs:
Unset this entity as a "High Priority Track".
 The tasked Platform is responsible for maintaining a list of current High-Priority tracks.

SetTransmitState.docs: Set the transmit state of an RF Platform such as a Radar, Beacon, or Radio.

SetSurveillanceState.docs: Set the surveillance state of a passive (listen-only) RF Platform.

SetEmissionControlState.docs:
Set whether or not an RF Platform has Emmission Control (EmCon).
 If supported, RF platforms should only expose the SetTransmitState task when EmissionControlState is EMISSION_CONTROL_STATE_ALLOWED.
 When in EMISSION_CONTROL_STATE_NOT_ALLOWED, the Platform should be in TRANSMIT_STATE_NOT_TRANSMITTING, and should remove SetTransmitState from the task Catalog.

Objective.docs: Describes the objective of a task.

LineFormation.docs: Maps to a Line formation of assets with a speed. This is a simple line with two LLAs.

Marshal.docs:
Maps to BREVITY code Marshal.
 Establish(ed) at a specific point, typically used to posture forces in preparation for an offensive operation.

Transit.docs:
Maps to UCI code RoutePlan.
 Used to command a platform between locations by requesting to make this RoutePlan the single primary active route.

TeamTransit.docs:
TeamTransit represents moving a team of vehicles into a zone.
 The specifics of how each vehicle in the team behaves is determined by the specific autonomy logic.

values.docs:
Zone for an autonomous asset to nose-dive into
 when its assignment has been concluded

ControlArea.docs: Models a Control Area within which Agents must operate.

OrbitDirection.docs: Direction of the loiter relative to the front of the vehicle.

VisualId.docs: Maps to BREVITY code ID with type Visual.

Loiter.docs: Maps to the Loiter behavior within the FlightTask type within UCI v2.

AreaSearch.docs: Represents intent to search an area. Maps to the Area Search Team Task within the Mission Autonomy Task Model.

VolumeSearch.docs: Represents intent to search a volume. Maps to the Volume Search Team Task within the Mission Autonomy Task Model.

ImproveTrackQuality.docs: Task to improve the quality of a track. Maps to the Improve Track Task within the Mission Autonomy Task Model.

Shadow.docs: Indicates intent to follow an Objective. Maps to Brevity code SHADOW.

Prior.docs: A Prior that can be used to inform an ISR Task.

AzimuthElevationPoint.docs: Celestial location with respect to a platform frame.

FramePoint.docs: Point clicked in the frame of the video feed.

GimbalZoom.docs: Command for setting gimbal zoom levels.

Monitor.docs:
Maps to BREVITY code ID with type MONITOR. To task assets to maintain sensor awareness
 on a given objective.

Scan.docs: Maps to BREVITY code ID with type SCAN. To task assets to find and report any tracks in a geographic area.

BattleDamageAssessment.docs: Performs a Battle Damage Assessment (BDA). Does not map to any Task in either UCI or BREVITY.

ReleasePayload.docs: Releases a payload from the vehicle

Grid.docs: A 2d grid with binary values for each grid cell.

endpoints.docs:
Create or update an entity and get a response confirming whether the Entity Manager API succesfully processes
 the entity. Ideal for testing environments.
 When publishing an entity, only your integration can modify or delete that entity; other sources, such as the
 UI or other integrations, can't. If you're pushing entity updates so fast that your publish task can't keep
 up with your update rate (a rough estimate of >= 1 Hz), use the PublishEntities request instead.

Create or update one or more entities rapidly using PublishEntities, which doesn't return error messages
 for invalid entities or provide server feedback. When publishing entities, only your integration can
 modify or delete those entities; other sources, such as the UI or other integrations, can't.
 When you use PublishEntities, you gain higher throughput at the expense of receiving no server responses or
 validation. In addition, due to gRPC stream mechanics, you risk losing messages queued on the outgoing gRPC
 buffer if the stream connection is lost prior to the messages being sent. If you need validation responses,
 are developing in testing environments, or have lower entity update rates, use PublishEntity.
Get an entity using its entityId.

Override an Entity Component. An override is a definitive change to entity data. Any authorized user of service
 can override overridable components on any entity. Only fields marked with overridable can be overridden.
 When setting an override, the user or service setting the override is asserting that they are certain of the change
 and the truth behind it.
Remove an override for an Entity component.
Returns a stream of entities with specified components populated.
Find Tasks that match request criteria.
Update the status of a Task.

Stream Tasks ready for RPC Agent execution that match agent selector (ex: entity_ids).
 Intended for use by Taskable Agents that need to receive Tasks ready for execution by RPC.
